solutions.content:
**1. Backtracking**
	Backtracking template is Goal, Search Space & Constraint.

	```
		public void backTracking() {
			// GOAL(Here we need to check what do we want in the end, 
			// in our question the GOAL is to reach the bottom right index)

			// SEARCH SPACE(Here we basically iterate through 
			// every possible move from current position, 
			// in our question it is either moving to right or down)

			// CONSTRAINT(Here we need to check 
			// whether the above chosen move is valid or not, here in our question 
			// the CONSTRAINT is that the chosen move should be within the boundaries)
		}
	```

With the above being said, BackTracking Solution below
``` 
class Solution {
    private int res;
    public int minPathSum(int[][] arr) {
        int m = arr.length;
        int n = arr[0].length;
        res = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        backTrack(arr, 0, 0, m-1, n-1, arr[0][0]);
        return res;
    }

    private int x[] = new int[]{0, 1};
    private int y[] = new int[]{1, 0};
    private void backTrack(int arr[][], int a, int b, int c, int d, int cur) {
		// GOAL
        if(a == c && b == d) {
            res = Math.min(res, cur);
            return ;
        }

		// SEARCH SPACE
        for(int i=0;i<2;i++) {
            int nx = a + x[i];
            int ny = b + y[i];
			// CONSTRAINT
            if(isSafe(nx, ny, c, d)) {
                backTrack(arr, nx, ny, c, d, cur+arr[nx][ny]);
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean isSafe(int a, int b, int c, int d) {
        return a >= 0 && b >= 0 && a <= c && b <= d;
    }
}
```

The above solution gives **TLE** because it takes every possible path into consideration.

2. **Recursive** approach

	This problem pattern is similar to **"With, Without"** classic principle.

	At each and every position , we have 2 choices in our given question. We can either go to the right or we can go to down. And we need to take the minimum of those 2 choices.

	Let's just say that we are at position (a, b) & the array is arr[][] & the number of rows as m and the number of columns as n.

	The recursive function goes like this:
	```
	function(int a, int b, int m, int n, int arr[][]) {

		// Handle base case 
		// which is when we reach our desired bottom right position
		if(a == m-1 && b == n-1) {
			return arr[a][b];
		}

		// Handle out of boundary cases
		if(a >= m || b >= n)
            return Integer.MAX_VALUE;


		// Below means that we can take the current pos value 
		// and we are taking the minimum of right & down
		return arr[a][b] + Math.min(function(a, b+1, m, n, arr), function(a+1, b, m, n, arr));
	}
	```

	I have used a Map to cache the already calculated results

	With that being said , Recursive solution below

	```
	class Solution {
    private Map<String, Integer> map;
    public int minPathSum(int[][] arr) {
        int m = arr.length;
        int n = arr[0].length;
        map = new HashMap<>();
        return recur(arr, 0, 0, m, n);
    }

    private int recur(int arr[][], int a, int b, int c, int d) {
        if(a == c-1 && b == d-1)
            return arr[a][b];
        if(a >= c || b >= d)
            return Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        String key = String.valueOf(a) + "," + String.valueOf(b);
        if(map.containsKey(key))
            return map.get(key);
        int res = arr[a][b] + Math.min(
            recur(arr, a, b+1, c, d),
            recur(arr, a+1, b, c, d)
        );
        map.put(key, res);
        return res;
    }
}
	```
3. **Dynamic Programming** approach

Once we write the recursive approach, DP is easy to write.

DP Solution below.
```
class Solution {
    public int minPathSum(int[][] arr) {
        int m = arr.length;
        int n = arr[0].length;
        return dy(arr);
    }

    private int dy(int arr[][]) {
        int m = arr.length;
        int n = arr[0].length;
        int dp[][] = new int[m][n];
        for(int i=0;i<m;i++) {
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++) {
                if( i == 0 && j == 0) {
                    dp[i][j] = arr[i][j];
                    continue;
                }
                dp[i][j] = arr[i][j] + Math.min(j > 0 ? dp[i][j-1] : Integer.MAX_VALUE, i > 0 ? dp[i-1][j] : Integer.MAX_VALUE);
            }
        }
        return dp[m-1][n-1];
    }
}
