# Approach
The minPathSum function initializes a 2D vector dp with dimensions n x m+1 and initializes all elements to -1. This dp array will be used to memoize the results of subproblems to avoid redundant calculations.

It calls the solve function with the given grid, the starting indices (n-1, m-1), and the dp array.

The solve function is a recursive function with memoization. It takes the current cell (i, j) in the grid and calculates the minimum path sum from the top-left corner to that cell.

If (i, j) is the top-left corner (i.e., i == 0 and j == 0), it returns the value in that cell because there's only one path to reach that cell.

If (i, j) is out of bounds (i.e., i < 0 or j < 0), it returns a large value (1e9) to indicate that this path is not valid.

If the result for (i, j) is already calculated and stored in the dp array, it returns that result to avoid redundant computation.

If the result for (i, j) is not calculated, it recursively calculates the minimum path sum by considering two possible moves:

Moving up (i.e., (i-1, j)) and adding the current cell's value to it.
Moving left (i.e., (i, j-1)) and adding the current cell's value to it.
It stores the minimum of these two values in the dp array at position (i, j) and returns that minimum value.

Finally, the minPathSum function returns the result obtained by calling solve with the bottom-right corner cell (n-1, m-1).

This approach effectively uses memoization to avoid redundant calculations and finds the minimum path sum efficiently. The result returned by minPathSum is the minimum sum required to reach the bottom-right corner of the grid while moving only right or down.
