# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
As in many solution the idea of pointers is being used to select the next element. I instead used  multilevel queues to keep track of the next element. The idea was simple that we will get the next element only by multiplying 2,3 or 5 with the existing element.The smallest element we can get by multiplying 2,3or 5 with existing ones which is unique one will be the next candidate.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We will build three queues q2 (will contain the elements that are to be multiplied with 2), q3 and q5 vis versa where q2 to q5 is increasing level. Now all new elements will be pushed in the q2 first (as multiplying a number with 2 will yeild a smaller number than with 3 or 5). We will select the front elements of all the queues and multiply with respective numbers and choose the minimum. Now after getting the minimum we have to move the element selected to the next level queue and pop it from the current queue.
Dry Run
Initially
q2 :1
q3 :empty
q5 :empty

i=1
ans=1*2
q2 :2
q3 :1
q5 :empty

i=2
ans=min(2*2,1*3)
q2 :2,3
q3 :
q5 :1

i=3
ans=min(2*2,1*5)
q2 :3,4
q3 :2
q5 :1

i=4
ans=min(2*3,3*2,5*1)
q2 :3,4,5
q3 :2
q5 :

i=5
ans=min(2*3,3*2) 
[Now here both the queue top yeilds the same result so we will pop    the numbers from all queues to next level queues and push the result as it is to the q2
]
q2 :4,5,6
q3 :3
q5 :2

.....so on upto n

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int nthUglyNumber(int n) 
    {
        int ans=1;
        queue <int> q2;
        queue <int> q3;
        queue <int> q5;
        unordered_map <int,bool> h_map;

        q2.push(1);
        h_map[1]=true;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
        {
            ans=q2.front()*2;
            if(!q3.empty() && (double)q3.front()*3<=INT_MAX) //check for interger overflow & queue underflow error
                ans=min(ans,q3.front()*3);
            if(!q5.empty()&& (double)q5.front()*5<=INT_MAX)
                ans=min(ans,q5.front()*5);
            q2.push(ans);
            h_map[ans]=true;
            //checking element from which queue was selected and poping it to the next queue.
            if(ans==q2.front()*2)   
            {
                q3.push(q2.front());
                q2.pop();                
            }
            else if(ans==q3.front()*3)
            {
                q5.push(q3.front());
                q3.pop();
            }
            else 
            {
                q5.pop(); 
            }
            // checking for any duplicates using a map
            if(!q3.empty() &&(double)q3.front()*3<=INT_MAX&& h_map.find(q3.front()*3)!=h_map.end())
                q3.pop();
            else if(!q5.empty() &&(double)q5.front()*5<=INT_MAX&& h_map.find(q5.front()*5)!=h_map.end())
                q5.pop();
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

