When I was working on this solution, it took me 4+ hours. Even after solving the problem, it seems more than a medium level problem to me. The 2 main reasons which made it hard for me to solve it were:

1. I did not understand the meaning of "forcing a win".
2. I tried to solve from 2 players point of view.

After reading many answers in discussion, I understood my answer to the first question as (p1: Player 1; p2: player2):-

**p1 takes a number n1 (from the pool of available numbers). After taking n1, the turn is passed to p2. Now, if p2 picks ANY number (from the pool of available numbers) and still loses, then we say that p1 has forced a win on p2**.

After this, it became clear as to how the recursion will work in this question. First, let's define a recursive function:-
**fn(*sumRemaining*,*isFirstPlayerTurn*,*taken*): fn is the helper function which returns true if the firstPlayer can force a win when we have *sumRemaining* value left to be crossed, with *taken* values already taken and currently *isFirstPlayerTurn* player has to play**

Now, once we have defined the recursive function in words, lets create a recursive formula:-
```
private boolean fn(int sumRemaining, boolean isFirstPlayerTurn, boolean[] taken) {
        if(sumRemaining <= 0) {
            /**
             * If it is 2nd players turn at this state, it means it as first players turn in previous state.
             * Thus, if our sumRemaining <= 0 now, it means 1st player took the winning number, and thus, he/she won.
             */
            return !isFirstPlayerTurn;
        }
        boolean ans = false;
        if(isFirstPlayerTurn) {
            for(int j = taken.length-1; j >= 1; j--) {
                if(!taken[j]) {
                    taken[j] = true;
                    /**
                     * First player plays, and it only needs one win.
                     * If first player wins in any case, we will return true (as per our definition of function).
                     */
                    if(fn(sumRemaining - j, !isFirstPlayerTurn, taken)) {
                        taken[j] = false;
                        return true;
                    }
                    taken[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }
        else {
            ans = true;
            for(int j = taken.length-1; j >= 1; j--) {
                if(!taken[j]) {
                    taken[j] = true;
                    /**
                     * 2nd player is playing, and he/she is trying all the values that are available. 
                     * In order for this function (fn(....)) to return true, 2nd player has to fail in all his/her attempts. 
                     * That means fn(sumRemaining - j,...) MUST RETURN TRUE IN ALL CASES (implying that player1 won in all cases).
                     * Hence, fn(...) for all cases should return true, for this function to return true. Else it should return false.
                     */
                    ans = ans && fn(sumRemaining - j, !isFirstPlayerTurn, taken);
                    taken[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

Denoting maximumChoosableInteger as m and desiredTotal as n.
Time complexity: n!. Time complexity would depend on the TOTAL number of branches in the recursion tree, and also on the amount spent per node of the tree. Amount spent per node: O(m). Also, TOTAL number of branches: 
At L1: m
At L2: m*(m-1)
At L3: m*(m-1)\*(m-2)
....
At Ln: m!

Thus, total nodes: m + m\*(m-1) + m\*m(-1)\*(m-2)\*...........\*m!
For taking the higher limit, abstract all of them out as factorials, to get,
O(total nodes): m! * m.
Since all nodes take O(m) time to operate, we can say **O(time): m^2 \* m!**

Given our question constraints, this time would force a TLE.

Let's memoize it. There are 3 candidates for memoization: sumRemaining, isFirstPlayerTurn and taken[]. But since sumRemaining can be taken out by combining values from taken[], we can ignore sumRemaining variable. But what about isFirstPlayerTurn?
Player1 and Player2 fill the taken[] boolean array in the same format (taking the last available value) and player1 always goes first. Hence, if we only memoize based on taken[] array, it would work. There won't be any case when for the same state of taken[] array, we have both players turn possible (that is, if taken = [0,1,0,0,1,0], then at this state, it could be only p1 OR p2's turn, but not both.

Hence, We only need taken[] array as our memoization medium. Let's do it then:

```
private Map<String, Boolean> dp = new HashMap<>();
private boolean fn(int sumRemaining, boolean isFirstPlayerTurn, boolean[] taken) {
        if(sumRemaining <= 0) {
            return !isFirstPlayerTurn;
        }
        String key = Arrays.toString(taken);
        if(dp.containsKey(key)) {
            return dp.get(key);
        }
        boolean ans = false;
        if(isFirstPlayerTurn) {
            for(int j = taken.length-1; j >= 1; j--) {
                if(!taken[j]) {
                    taken[j] = true;
                    if(fn(sumRemaining - j, !isFirstPlayerTurn, taken)) {
                        taken[j] = false;
                        ans = true;
						break;
                    }
                    taken[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }
        else {
            ans = true;
            for(int j = taken.length-1; j >= 1; j--) {
                if(!taken[j]) {
                    taken[j] = true;
                    ans = ans && fn(sumRemaining - j, !isFirstPlayerTurn, taken);
                    taken[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }
        dp.put(key, ans);
        return ans;
    }
```

Fun fact: Still TLE. Why? What's the complexity? Since we are memoizing on the state of taken[] array at any point, we can have 2^m (m: maximumChoosableInteger) nodes (since every index on taken[] array could be filled with only 2 values: true or false). Also, time taken per node: O(m). **Thus, total time complexity right now: m \* O(2^m).**

BUT, by saying so, we are ignoring the time to search in hash map (The HUGE string that we are storing in the map and then retrieving it). It is taking a lot of time. Hence, we optimize it by converting our hash map keys from String to Integer. We do this by leveraging a constraint: The maximum length of taken[] could be 20 (thus, fitting easily inside a 32bit integer). Hence, using this, we get the following AC solution:

```
