The idea is almost the same with other posts in discussion: just using DFS to search all possibilities and optimizing DFS with memoization (`lru_cache`). 

But to avoid TLE, I first try to quickly handle two special corner cases and then use DFS.

And also, I write it in a pythonic way to make my solution **conciser and easier to understand**.

If you skip lines for handling special cases, it's just 6 lines.
```python
import functools
class Solution:
    # Algorithm: DFS (with cache)
    # Time: O(2^n)
    # Space: O(2^n)
    def canIWin(self, maxChoosableInteger: int, desiredTotal: int) -> bool:
        # quickly handle two special cases
        sum_of_all = (maxChoosableInteger + 1) * maxChoosableInteger // 2
        if sum_of_all < desiredTotal:
            return False
        if sum_of_all == desiredTotal:
            return maxChoosableInteger % 2 == 1
        @functools.lru_cache(None)
        def can_i_win(options, target):
            if options[-1] >= target:
                return True
            return not all(can_i_win(options[:i] + options[i + 1:],target - x) for i, x in enumerate(options))

        return can_i_win(tuple(range(1, maxChoosableInteger + 1)), desiredTotal)
```

