solutions.content:
- The code has variables with names easy to read. Please check it out!

- Some details to be careful:
	1. to use lru_cache, make every argument to be int or tuple.
	2. The order matters:  ```choose number -> check win or not -> if not, switch to opponent's turn```
		( It will be wrong in this order: ```check win or not -> choose number```)
	3. there are cases both players cannot reach the ```desiredTotal```, check this at begining

```
class Solution:
    def canIWin(self, N: int, desiredTotal: int) -> bool:
        if (1+N)*N // 2 < desiredTotal: return False

        @lru_cache(None)
        def dp(cur, curpool):

            for i in range(len(curpool)):

                new = cur + curpool[i]

                win_rightnow = (new >= desiredTotal)
                if win_rightnow: 
                    return True

                opponent_win = dp(new, curpool[:i]+curpool[i+1:])
                if not opponent_win: 
                    return True

            return False

        pool = tuple(range(1,N+1))
        return dp(0, pool)
```

