solutions.content:
There already exist several detailed posts explaining the top-down dynamic programming. What made me write this post is that most (if not **ALL**) of the solutions performed their bit manipulations directly on primitive data types (like `int`) to represent a set, which is so-called *bit masking* technique (or formally, bit set / bit map).

The problem description shows that max choosable number is at most 20, and those who've practiced bit masking problems will come up with this method right away.
However, bit masking itself is nothing more than a fancy bit-wise implementation of a set. It doesn't essentially relate to any algorithm, though it's mostly used in DP problems.

I would say that bit map is somewhat useful in real world, such as marking a disk sector as available or occupied. However, it's **NOT** a good practice to do bit-wise operation directly on integers to represent a set. From the perspective of readability and maintainability, it should be encapsulated / decoupled into a class or at least a macro in programming languages without object oriented programming paradigm.

Java provides a decent `BitSet` class to fulfill the task.
```
class Solution {
    Map<BitSet, Boolean> memo = new HashMap<>();

    public boolean canIWin(int limit, int desired) {
        if (desired <= limit) return true;

        int sum = limit * (limit + 1) / 2;
        if (sum < desired) return false;
        if (sum == desired) return limit % 2 == 1;

        var used = new BitSet(limit);

        return isWinnable(used, desired, limit);
    }

    private boolean isWinnable(BitSet used, int desired, int limit) {
        if (desired <= 0) return false;

        // Not satisfied with explicit type casting here, but no better method to copy bitset
        var original = (BitSet)used.clone();
        if (memo.containsKey(original)) return memo.get(original);

        var winnable = false;
        for (int i = used.nextClearBit(0); i < limit; i = used.nextClearBit(i + 1)) {
            if (used.get(i)) continue;

            used.set(i);
            winnable = !isWinnable(used, desired - (i + 1), limit);
            used.clear(i);

            if (winnable) break;
        }

        memo.put(original, winnable);
        return winnable;
    }
}
```

