# Intuition
The general approach to take in game problems like these is to try, as a first priority, a function that will play optimally for any player. It will be a function that given a state of the game will return whether such game state is winnable.

Why follow this approach? As far as I know, this is the simplest form a function can take, a function that is ignorant of whose turn it is. And as it is in the simplest form, it is easier to think about such function and therefore we can do a quick check whether it's actually in a sufficient form.

Luckily for us it is sufficient for this problem! The state of the game is in fact defined by what has been taken previously and the current sum (score).  
* If the current sum (score) is lower than the target (`desiredTotal`) then we are still in a game and we can try any of the moves available to us that are left in the set of available moves.
* Otherwise, we have arrived at a state that was passed to us by another player and that player made a winning move (i.e taking the score to the finish line). Here we return that we have lost.

In principle, that is all that we need. Maybe we just need to brush up some semantics.

# Approach
We would like to have a way to know what's the state of the current game. There are two important parameters that can help us make our next decision:
* Available moves - it's a set of moves that we are left with at this certain state of the game. Initially, we can take any number from `[1 ... N]` inclusive (N being `maxChoosableInteger`). As we are about to take some number from this set and pass the new game state to the next player, we must remove that number from the set. This whole procedure of keeping what numbers are still available can be achieved with a `bitset`. `bitset` can tell us whether certain number has been taken with a bit `1` or `0` otherwise. So all we need to do is mark the position of the taken number. Somewhat from experience and historically this is done using just an `int` variable (and that's what I have), but I would prefer to see people use bitset instead.
* Current sum score - this is a simpler parameter, just a current total score (running score of the game). This parameter helps us determine whether our game comes to an end. At a point when this score is greater or equal to `desiredTotal` we should stop the game. Anywhere in between it's nice to keep track of this parameter (because we need it, though I guess we can just reduce our `desiredTotal` to zero instead). 

Partial note: while sum (score) parameter is nice to keep track of, it's a redundant state parameter. In fact, our bitmask already can tell us how much score we have at that bitmask state. Carrying sum score is therefore only a nice thing to have as computing score from the bitmask itself takes a bit of time, but sum (score) is not a necessary state indicator. That is we do not need, in a sense of DP, to have `dp[mask][sum]` situation, as `mask` parameter can have only one `sum` related to it. `dp[mask]` is a sufficient game state.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n * 2^n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(2^n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
int dfs(int mask, int sum, int n, int t, vector <int> &dp) {
    if (sum >= t) // Base Case
        return false; // we lost by now
    if (dp[mask] != -1) // Memo check
        return dp[mask]; // return what we found before
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if ((mask & (1 << i)) == 0) { // available?
            if (!dfs(mask ^ (1 << i), sum + i + 1, n, t, dp))
                return dp[mask] = true;
            // the if statement checks if the opponent loses
            // if opponent loses at any of our available moves
            // that means we are going to win in this state.
        }
    }
    return dp[mask] = false;
}
bool canIWin(int n, int t) {
    if (t == 0) // edge case 1: not a game
        return true;
    if (n * (n + 1) / 2 < t) // edge case 2: never enough
        return false;
    vector <int> dp(1 << n, -1);
    return dfs(0, 0, n, t, dp);
}
```

Playing around a little with bitset:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int canWin(bitset <20> mask, int sum, int n, vector <int> &dp) {
        if (sum <= 0) // Base Case
            return false; // we have lost by now
        auto &memo = dp[mask.to_ulong()];
        if (memo != -1) // Memo check
            return memo; // return what we found before
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (mask.test(i) == 0) { // available?
                if (!canWin(mask ^ (bitset <20>(1 << i)), sum - i - 1, n, dp))
                    return memo = true;
                // the if statement checks if the opponent loses
                // if opponent loses at any of our available moves
                // that means we are going to win in this state.
            }
        }
        return memo = false;
    }
    bool canIWin(int n, int desiredTotal) {
        if (desiredTotal == 0) // edge case 1: not a game
            return true;
        if (n * (n + 1) / 2 < desiredTotal) // edge case 2: never enough
            return false;
        vector <int> dp(1 << n, -1);
        return canWin(bitset <20>(0), desiredTotal, n, dp);
    }
};
```

Not sure if I like `bitset <20>` here, but as an exploration it was worth a try :)

