# Code
```
// DP Solution: Recursion with Memory
// Use bit map to represent the used boolean array. (used.length <= 21)
// Time complexity: O(2^N), where N = maxChoosableInteger
// Space complexity: O(2^N)
class Solution {
    public boolean canIWin(int maxChoosableInteger, int desiredTotal) {
        int sum = maxChoosableInteger * (maxChoosableInteger + 1) / 2;
        if(sum < desiredTotal) return false;
        if(desiredTotal <= 0) return true;
        boolean[] used = new boolean[maxChoosableInteger + 1];
        Map<Integer, Boolean> memo = new HashMap<>();
        return canIWin(0, desiredTotal, used, memo);
    }

    private boolean canIWin(int sum, int desiredTotal, boolean[] used, Map<Integer, Boolean> memo) {
        if (sum >= desiredTotal) return false;
        int bit = bitMap(used);
        Boolean status = memo.get(bit);
        if (status != null) return status;
        // If the opponent always win or I always lose, then win is false
        for (int i = 1; i < used.length; i++) {
            if (!used[i]) {
                used[i] = true;
                status = !canIWin(sum + i, desiredTotal, used, memo);
                used[i] = false;
                if (status) break;
            }
        }
        memo.put(bit, status);
        return status;
    }

    private int bitMap(boolean[] used) {
        int bit = 0;
        for (boolean v : used) {
            bit <<= 1;
            if (v) {
                bit |= 1;
            }
        }
        return bit;
    }
}
```
Same idea with bitmap optimization. we don't need to compute bitMap each time.

